The aromatic region in the 1H-NMR spectrum of piloquinone consists of a singlet at 7.32 ppm, doublets at 6.97 ppm and 7.42 ppm, and a triplet at 7.58 ppm. The singlet belongs to H-4 and the triplet to H-6. The doublet at 6.97 ppm certainly be- longs to H-7, caused by the shielding effect of the ortho- hydroxy group. This was confirmed by NOE difference meas- urements; irradiation at H-4 resulted in a very strong NOE (24%) at H-5, confirming that the chemical shift of H-5 is 7.42 ppm and, by extension, the chemical shift of H-7 must be 6.97 ppm. Abstract: Complete 1H- and 13C-NMR spectral data of piloquinone are presented. The chemical shifts were confirmed through correlation spectroscopy and NOE measurements. The structure of piloquinone, a brown red pigment isolated from the mycelium of Streptomyces pilosus Ettlinger, was de— termined in the 1960's by IR, 1H-NMR, and mass spectroscopic methods (1 —4). Later, its structure was confirmed by synthesis (5). Owing to the lack of modern NMR equipment, however, no 13C-NMR spectral data were given. Moreover, at that time, 1H chemical shifts of the aromatic protons H-5 and H-7 and the two phenolic protons were determined by running spectra of several derivatives of piloquinone and comparing the data with those of piloquinone itself (3). We now present the complete 1H- and 13C-NMR chemical shifts of piloquinone (Table 1), as confirmed by correlation spectroscopy and NOE difference measurements.
